  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Architecture Envisioning&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A common practice is to perform architectural modeling at a high level in early stages of the project lifecycle. This&#xD;
    helps the team and stakeholders reach agreement about the technical strategy to be followed in the project. There are&#xD;
    many advantages of doing this initial architectural modeling, including improved productivity, reduced technical risks,&#xD;
    reduced development time, improved communication and team organization, and ability to scale agile software&#xD;
    development.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The objective of architecture envisioning is not to create heavy documentation, but&amp;nbsp;identify an architectural&#xD;
    strategy to be followed by the team. You can use free-form diagrams to capture the discussions around how the team&#xD;
    members think they will build the system. The design for that strategy is done in more details later in the project&#xD;
    lifecycle.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For more information on architecture envisioning,&amp;nbsp;visit&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.agilemodeling.com/essays/initialArchitectureModeling.htm&quot;>http://www.agilemodeling.com/essays/initialArchitectureModeling.htm&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
